title: Peronet House
description:
Perronet House is an eleven storey residential tower block in the heart of South London's Elephant & Castle. In 1969 Sir Roger Walters was commissioned by the Greater London Council to design a high density block of social housing to compliment the already completed high rise buildings of commercial, educational and governmental establishments. It won a commendation in the 1971 Good Design In Housing awards.

It is a building of fascinating quirks, both structurally and socially. Flats are situated on a raised "P" (for PODIUM) level, and on the 2nd, 4th, 6th, 8th and 10th floor. The P level flats are a later 1980s addition but all the flats above it are split level, arranged over three primary floors and wrapped around a central communal corridor. This provides each flat with a dual aspect unobstructed by external corridors more usually found on high rise social housing in the area.

title: Kennington Cross
description: Area around junction of Kennington Road and Kennington Lane. Kennington Cross was recently remodelled with good pedestrian crossings and street furniture. There are several restaurants and a couple of pubs in the area. Features at the crossroads include an old horse trough now filled with plants and old victorian public toilets now only opened on special occasions for visitors to view their architecture.

urlhtml: Christ Church and Upton Chapel Church.co.uk Waterloo
title: Christ Church and Upton Chapel Church.co.uk Waterloo
description:
Church.co.uk, Waterloo, which began its life as Surrey Chapel in 1783, was to become a major influence in the birth and early development of the Ragged School movement and ran a full medical service for the poor. It reached the height of its influence in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, with a regular congregation of well over 2000 people.

However, in September 2003, with a congregation down to just 20 people, Christ Church & Upton Chapel, as the former Surrey Chapel was by then known, asked Oasis Trust to join it in developing a new, united, central London, renamed as Church.co.uk (CCU), Waterloo soon after.

Cafe with internet access open in the day during the week
